Subject: appraisal
Value: An appraisal is a cognitive representation which represents an evaluation of the relevance of some triggering object or event to the organism.

Subject: anger
Value: <Anger is a negative emotion, characterised by feelings of unpleasantness and high arousal, in the form of antagonistic feelings and action tendencies. [Source: OCEAS]>

Subject: appraisal of suddenness
Value: An appraisal which represents an evaluation of how suddenly an event occurred.

Subject: appraisal of familiarity
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of how familiar an object or event is.

Subject: appraisal of predictability
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of how predictable an event was.

Subject: appraisal of expectedness
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of whether an event was expected to occur.

Subject: appraisal of pleasantness
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of the pleasantness of an object or event.

Subject: appraisal as sudden
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event occurred suddenly.

Subject: appraisal as not sudden
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event did not occur suddenly.

Subject: appraisal as familiar
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an object or event is familiar.

Subject: appraisal as not familiar
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an object or event is not familiar.

Subject: appraisal as predictable
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event was easy to predict.

Subject: appraisal as not predictable
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event was not easy to predict.

Subject: appraisal as expected
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event was expected.

Subject: appraisal of goal importance
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of whether an event or object is important to the person's goals or needs.

Subject: evaluation as important to goals
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that the event or object is important to the person's goals or needs.

Subject: evaluation as not important to goals
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that the event or object is not important to the person's goals or needs.

Subject: appraisal of causal agency
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of who or what caused an event.

Subject: appraisal as caused by chance
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event was caused by chance.

Subject: feeling good
Value: The subjective emotional feeling of feeling good, positive.

Subject: appraisal as deliberate
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event was deliberately (intentionally) caused.

Subject: appraisal of desirability of consequences
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of the desirability of the expected consequences of an event.

Subject: appraisal as desirable consequences
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that the expected consequences of an event are desirable.

Subject: appraisal as undesirable consequences
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that the expected consequences of an event are undesirable.

Subject: appraisal of urgency of response
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation of the urgency of responding to an event.

Subject: appraisal as urgent response
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event requires an urgent (immediate) response.

Subject: appraisal as not urgent response
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that an event does not require an urgent response.

Subject: appraisal of avoidability of consequences
Value: An appraisal which represents a judgement about how avoidable the expected consequences of an event will be.

Subject: appraisal as avoidable consequences
Value: An appraisal that represents a judgement that the expected consequences of an event are in principle avoidable or modfiable.

Subject: appraisal as unavoidable consequences
Value: An appraisal that represents a judgement that the expected consequences of an event will be difficult to avoid or modify.

Subject: appraisal of congruence with ideals
Value: An appraisal which represents a judgement about whether an event is consistent with the person's standards or ideals.

Subject: appraisal as not congruent with ideals
Value: An appraisal that represents a judgement that an event is inconsistent with a person's standards or ideals.

Subject: appraisal of social attention
Value: An appraisal which represents a judgement about the direction and nature of the social attention surrounding an event.

Subject: appraisal as not being at the centre of attention
Value: An appraisal that represents a judgement that a person is not at the centre of the surrounding social attention.

Subject: appraisal of justice of treatment
Value: Appraisal which represents an evaluation of whether the person was treated justly or unjustly by another person.

Subject: appraisal as just treatment
Value: An appraisal which represents an evaluation that the person was treated justly by another person.

Subject: appraisal as unjust treatment
Value: An appraisal that represents an evaluation that the person was treated unjustly by another person. (Injustice.)

Subject: appraisal of loss
Value: An appraisal that represents a belief that something or someone that is important to the person has been lost to the person.

Subject: feeling at ease
Value: The subjective emotional feeling of being at ease, comfortable, relaxed.

Subject: feeling energetic
Value: The subjective emotional feeling of having lots of energy, being energetic.

Subject: feeling in control
Value: The subjective emotional feeling that one is in control of oneself, that one is fully the agent of one's behavior.

Subject: feeling restless
Value: The subjective emotional feeling of restlessness, a state of not being calm, of an agitation to do something.

Subject: feeling calm
Value: The subjective feeling of being calm, being relaxed, being at peace.

Subject: feeling out of control
Value: The subjective feeling of not being in control, not being able to gain agency of one's own behavior.

Subject: feeling strong
Value: The subjective feeling of strength, capability, energy and capacity to do things.

Subject: feeling weak
Value: The subjective feeling of weakness, lack of energy and/or capability, faintness, absence of strength.

Subject: feeling alert
Value: The subjective feeling of being wide awake, alert, having active attention and perception.

Subject: facial expression behaviour
Value: A behavioural process that involves a change in the expression of the face.

Subject: smiling
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the person smiles.

Subject: pressing lips together
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the lips are tightly pressed together.

Subject: raising eyebrows
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the eyebrows are raised.

Subject: frowning
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the person frowns.

Subject: closing eyes
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the eyes are closed.

Subject: opening eyes widely
Value: A facial expression behaviour in which the eyes are opened widely.

Subject: neutral expression
Value: A facial expression behaviour which appears very neutral (showing no expression).

Subject: moving away from people
Value: A bodily movement behaviour which involves moving, or leaning, away from people (avoidance).

Subject: staying still
Value: A bodily movement behaviour which involves remaining still.

Subject: speaking loudly
Value: Speaking with a voice louder than usual.

Subject: speaking with trembling voice
Value: Speaking with a voice that is hesitant or trembling.

Subject: not speaking
Value: Remaining silent, not producing spoken utterances.

Subject: speaking a long utterance
Value: Speaking behaviour in which a long utterance is produced.

Subject: speaking with altered speech melody
Value: Speaking with an altered rhythm or melody of speech relative to the norm for that person.

Subject: speaking in a disturbed fashion
Value: Speaking in a manner which is disturbed relative to what is the norm for that person.

Subject: speaking at a slower rate
Value: Speaking in a manner that is slower than the norm for that person.

Subject: panique
Value: A severe episode of fear with strong associated discomfort and thoughts of impending harm.

Subject: canonical angry facial expression
Value: The canonical facial expression associated with the experience of anger.

Subject: canonical emotional facial expression
Value: Characteristic facial expressions that are made when a person is undergoing a so-called \"basic\" emotions. These are canonical, that is, individual facial expressions when undergoing emotions can vary or not change at all. However, research indicates evidence for the existence of characteristic canonical facial expressions that are displayed when experiencing certain emotions even across cultures.

Subject: canonical fearful facial expression
Value: The canonical facial expression associated with the experience of fear.

Subject: schadenfreude
Value: A complex emotion that consists of the experience of pleasure as caused by the misfortune of others.

Subject: canonical happy facial expression
Value: The canonical facial expression associated with the experience of happiness.

Subject: canonical disgusted facial expression
Value: The canonical facial expression associated with the experience of disgust.

Subject: canonical sad facial expression
Value: The canonical facial expression associated with the experience of sadness.

Subject: canonical emotional voice utterances
Value: The vocal utterances associated with the characteristic sound of an emotion. Obviously, any particular emotional instance may be associated with a great variety of different types of voice utterances or no voice utterances at all. However, \"canonical\" or characteristic voice utterances can be associated with core emotions.

Subject: canonical disgusted voice utterance
Value: Voice utterances characteristically associated with the experience of disgust.

Subject: canonical surprised facial expression
Value: Characteristic facial expression made when a person is undergoing an experience of surprise.

Subject: irritable mood
Value: An irritable mood is a general feeling of mild annoyance, a heightened disposition to anger and other negatively valenced emotions.

Subject: emotional personality trait
Value: An emotional personality trait is a personality trait, a part of an overall personality, which predisposes the individual to repeated occurrences of a characteristic emotional process.

Subject: GO:0060273
Value: <http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MFOEM_000031>
